= Chapter 17: Natural Labor Induction: What Works and What Doesn't <ch-labor-induction>

== ONE-PAGE OVERVIEW

Waiting for baby to arrive past your due date can feel interminable. The internet offers dozens of "natural induction" methods, from eating dates to bouncing on exercise balls. Here's what the evidence actually shows.

=== Key Takeaways

1. _Nipple stimulation is the most effective natural method._ Research shows 37% of women went into labor within 72 hours compared to just 6% without it. It works by releasing your body's own oxytocin.

2. _Most methods only work if your body is already ready._ A favorable cervix (Bishop score of 6+) makes all approaches more successful. An unripe cervix won't respond to spicy food or walking marathons.

3. _Dates are surprisingly well-supported._ Eating 6 dates daily starting at 36 weeks may increase spontaneous labor, shorten labor duration, and improve cervical readiness at admission.

4. _Spicy food, birth balls, and pineapple are myths._ No evidence supports these popular methods for starting labor (though birth balls are great for comfort during labor).

5. _Risk increases gradually after 41 weeks._ The normal range for pregnancy is approximately 37 to 42 weeks. Stillbirth risk increases meaningfully beyond 42 weeks, which is why providers recommend closer monitoring and discuss delivery options as you approach that point. Going past your due date — especially as a first-time parent — is common and does not automatically mean induction is necessary.

=== Bottom Line

Try nipple stimulation and dates if you're past your due date with a ripening cervix. Castor oil appears effective but comes with significant gastrointestinal side effects — weigh that trade-off for yourself. Have the induction conversation with your provider at 40-41 weeks. Trust that your body knows what it's doing, and understand how the risk profile changes as pregnancy extends.

