== OUR TAKE

Birth is a physiological process that has worked for millions of years. When possible, letting that process unfold naturally respects the intricate hormonal dance between mother and baby. There's something to be said for trusting your body's timing.

But trust isn't blind faith. As pregnancy extends past 41 weeks, risks accumulate. The evidence clearly shows increased stillbirth rates after 42 weeks. The normal range for pregnancy is broad — roughly 37 to 42 weeks — and the evidence does show that risks increase with time, particularly beyond 42 weeks.

_Our recommendations:_

1. _At 39-40 weeks:_ Have the induction conversation. Know your Bishop score. Understand your options. No decisions needed yet unless there are medical concerns.

2. _At 40-41 weeks:_ Consider evidence-based natural methods if your cervix is favorable. Nipple stimulation and dates have real support. Membrane sweeping works for about half of candidates.

3. _At 41+ weeks:_ Enhanced monitoring is available and can help you track baby's well-being. Discuss induction timeline. Natural methods can continue, but have a plan.

4. _At 42 weeks:_ The evidence shows meaningfully increased risk at this point. For most pregnancies, induction becomes a strong consideration. Discuss the specific factors in your situation — including monitoring results, amniotic fluid levels, and placental function — with your provider.

5. _Castor oil is a personal call._ It works, but the gastrointestinal side effects are significant. Some families find the trade-off worthwhile; others prefer to avoid it.

6. _Skip the spicy food, pineapple, and bouncing._ No evidence, and heartburn before labor is unpleasant.

The evidence supports nipple stimulation, membrane sweeping, dates, and possibly sex and walking. Everything else is either unproven or not worth the side effects.

Most importantly: talk to your provider at 40 weeks. Make a plan together. Understand why they're recommending what they're recommending. Informed decision-making leads to better outcomes than either blind compliance or stubborn resistance.

Your body knows how to give birth. Your baby will signal when they're ready, most of the time. And when that signal doesn't come or can't be waited for, modern medicine offers safe paths forward. The best birth is the one that gets you and your baby through safely, whether labor starts on its own at 39 weeks or needs a nudge at 41.

